                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I really haven't been playing EQ much recently - the combination of general burnout plus the atrocious warping issues since the DX9 change really soured my enjoyment of the game. However, I recently started playing EQ lightly again, and have been having a bit of fun. My goal is to finish up Lightning Reflexes (just cuz <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />) and break out of the same ol' routine by going to new places and trying new things. So I soloed in the Acrylia Caverns a bit, had a decent time with a DC pet in the outer area, and then decided on a whim to try soloing again in GoD.
<br />

<br />
Now my previous charming experience in the GoD zones consisted of a couple dozen charm attempts a couple weeks after God was released - mostly in Riwwi, with a few charms in Barindu. So while my impressions were far from comprehensive, and I might've been the victim of the rng, charming in Riwwi was basically a huge pita. Charms lasted an incredibly short amount of time, and the fact you could get four or five unresistable procs of 600 a piece in about 3 seconds on a charm break meant that survivability was really low for recovering from a break. I remember going there with 4500 hp, arcane rune up, ER3 ready to go ... and zoning with about 300 hit points left and a dot on me in about 5 seconds. I had to gate to PoK and thankfully had a cleric at the small bank that healed me before I died. ie - Not fun.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I headed to Riwwi last night, and noticed a huuuuge difference.
<br />

<br />
First off, they actually dropped money. Not much mind you (maybe 5 plat a piece, if they do indeed drop anything), and not enough to make me go purely for the money, but it's something ... I guess.
<br />

<br />
Secondly, the mobs there proc A LOT less. A charm break is no longer death - having an add no longer means death. They can still take your hp down in a hurry (eating through an arcane rune in a few hits), but not having to content with three 600 point procs is nice. Twice I had an add, got stunned trying to mez, and was able to recast mez *without* AR being eaten, and without being procced on at all.
<br />

<br />
Thirdly, charms last a lot longer, in my opinion. My basic routine is to set up by the Barindu zone line, root, tash, charm, and then speed a mob, and give him two weapon. I then pull with slow and let my pet go at it. After root wears off, I move him to the centre of the hallway to Barindu and start pulling to him, then move beside the zone line to sit and med. Before I'd maybe be able to kill 2 mobs before charm broke and I'd have to zone. Now I was getting full duration charms most of the time, although I will mention that my last 3 charms each lasted under 1 minute - at that point I decided to call it a night. So maybe the previous charms were just the rng being kind to me. But my impression of the night was a lot more favourable.
<br />

<br />
However, the xp in Riwwi is still pretty bad, especially considering the rvr. Drops were non existant (besides the 4 gold sellable items you get - whooooooo), and I walked away with a single Sapphire as my biggest piece of loot. However, it was a fun challenge. I never had the luxury of being full mana, I had a few close calls, a couple of unexpected adds, and generally was always kept on my toes. Plus there are *some* drops there, and the possibility of such made things a bit more exciting.
<br />

<br />
While I didn't stay there all that long (maybe 45 minutes), I was able to fully clear "the promenade" in front of the Barindu zone, which I consider a pretty nice accomplishment. There's about 20 mobs that wander that area, and being able to clear them all before a respawn was a good feeling. It was extra exciting because halfway through the clearing, I had to kill off my pet (root and nuke), and had an add come in. I had him mezzed and was going to zone and med to full (was at about 40 mana) ... but figured what the hell. I tashed, charmed, hasted, and dual wielded him, and then started pulling again. Was great to be living on the edge, low on mana, medding like crazy ... and pull through. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
I also give Barindu a couple of tries, and also noticed vastly longer charm durations, and vastly decreased procs. I also noticed that mobs hit like frickin' trucks in there. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /> As a bonus, xp is at least decent, although you can't keep up the sustained xp rate of a place like Tactics or HoH. Still, I was able to kill 8 mobs (2 of which were pets) in very short order. Just be *sure* to keep root on, because mobs will run at 20%, and there's always a wanderer around, or the mob will always choose to run directly for that next set of static spawns around the corner. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
So that's my impression of Riwwi and Barindu, from a charmer's perspective. Not really worth the time on a typical night, but it's a fun change of pace, has some PoTactics like action in it, and the chance for a decent drop, while nearly non existant, is still there.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />It's easy to use - if you're one of the 2% of the population who thinks logically and can read an instruction manual. The other 98% of the population would find it very hard or impossible to use.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by QenyaStarfury on Thu Jun 03, 2004 10:56 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
